 > Before I was using a manual thread management, where I giving a task to a part of my program, everytime an order is place I have to give the task
        to another part of my comp, that's not efficient, but using an executorService, I make sure I assign it to a certain part of computer whic will
        overlook or task which are incoming however much.

    This is the old thread way below:

        for (int i = 0; i < threadCount; i++) {
            new Thread(() -> book.addOrder(new Order("BUY-" + System.nanoTime(), 100.0, 1, true))).start();
            new Thread(() -> book.addOrder(new Order("SELL-" + System.nanoTime(), 100.0, 1, false))).start();
        }
        ...

 > This was my codes still with a few 20 orders, before I refactor it to handle 100 orders:

 package org.igire.week1_shecancode_iro;


 import org.igire.week1_shecancode_iro.RealTimeOrderMatchingEngine.ThreadSafeOrderBook.Order;
 import org.igire.week1_shecancode_iro.RealTimeOrderMatchingEngine.ThreadSafeOrderBook.OrderBook;
 import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

 public class OrderBookTest {
     @Test
     public void testOrderBook() throws InterruptedException {
         OrderBook book = new OrderBook();
         int threadCount = 10;

         // Spawn 10 Buyers and 10 Sellers
         for (int i = 0; i < threadCount; i++) {
             new Thread(() -> book.addOrder(new Order("BUY-" + System.nanoTime(), 100.0, 1, true))).start();
             new Thread(() -> book.addOrder(new Order("SELL-" + System.nanoTime(), 100.0, 1, false))).start();
         }

         // Allow threads to complete their work
         Thread.sleep(1000);

         book.matchOrders();
         System.out.println("Simulation complete.");
     }
 }


        I implemented the professional way below in the OrderBookTest